misc¶

The training of the model requires a lot of computational resources. Thus, most of the tasks will be run on a cluster, such as ubelix (https://hpc-unibe-ch.github.io/). The misc folder provides bash file examples to run jobs. Feel free to customize and adapt them to your needs. Run the files in the following order:

sbatch job_single.sh
sbatch --dependency=afterok:<jobid> job_multi.sh

where <jobid> is the job id of the first job. The --dependency=afterok:<jobid> ensures that the second job is only started after the first job has finished successfully.

Important: Enter a valid e-mail address to the bash files!

Data¶

The images can be found in data/images/ and the CSV-files for the various subsets are located in data/set/.

data/images contains all images that were available at the start of the project, that is also the low quality ones. But don't worry; these images are not part of the CSV-files and are, therefore, never loaded.

Utility Functions¶

Multiple functions are housed within the file utils/util_functions.py. Among these, load_backbone(), load_datasets(), and the transformation functions play integral roles in both the training and evaluation setups, while the function evaluation() serves the purpose of model assessment. These functions are employed in the tasks, where they are required, below.

In [2]:
from utils.util_functions import load_backbone, load_datasets, test_transform, evaluation

DRDataset¶

The DRDataset is a custom PyTorch dataset. It is located under utils/DRDataset.py.

The best way to import the train and validation/test sets is through load_datasets().

Models¶

The models located in utils/Models.py are custom PyTorch nn.Module implementations. Moreover, a function to initialize the weights of the model with the Kaiming-He method is included.

The best way to load the backbone models is load_backbones().

In [7]:
from utils.Models import SingleModalityClassifier, MultiModalityClassifier, kaiming_init
from torchvision.models import resnet18, ResNet18_Weights
In [8]:
single_model = SingleModalityClassifier(feature_vector_size=256, backbone=resnet18, weights=ResNet18_Weights.IMAGENET1K_V1)
multi_model = MultiModalityClassifier(feature_vector_size=256, backbone=resnet18, weights={'fundus': None, 'horizontal': None, 'vertical': None}, stack_or_sum='stack', device=th.device('cpu'))
kaiming_init(multi_model)
In [9]:
resnet18, weights = load_backbone(backbone_str='resnet18', script_type='single')

Training¶

A dedicated script is provided at source/training.py to train a SingleModalityClassifieror a MultiModalityClassifier. When running the script, some required and optional arguments have to be passed. These include:

  • -t, --type Type of training ('full', 'cv' or 'none'). 'none' is evaluation only mode and requires a model trained in 'full' mode. Required.
  • -b, --backbone Backbone to be used ("resnet18", "resnet50" or "efficientnet"). Required.
  • -v, --feature_vector_size Size of the feature vector (0 - 1280). Required.
  • -m, --image_method Image modality or fusion method ("fundus", "horizontal", "vertical", "stack" or "sum"). Required.
  • -s, --batch_size Batch size (1 - 64). Default: 1.
  • -i, --image_size Image size (16 - 512). Default: 16.
  • -n, --name_suffix Suffix for the model name. Default: "".
  • -d, --data_suffix Suffix for the data CSV files ("" or "_refined"). Default: "".

Run the following code in your terminal:

python training.py -t full -b resnet18 -v 256 -m fundus -s 42 -i 128 -n _example

The training information (training loss, metrics, ...) is logged in an event file that can be read out with the TensorboardReader class. The model state is also saved.

TensorboardReader¶

During training, an event file is created. These files are stored in a folder in source. An example folder is provided in docs. To read out the data, the TensorboardReader class can be utilized.

The method info() provides an overview of the available data. If the tag is available, the following methods can be used to get the respective data (else, the methods return None):

  • get_fold(): Returns the fold number (only if training was done with --type='cv', else 0 is returned).
  • get_num_params(): Returns the number of parameters of the model.
  • get_epoch_length(): Returns the number of batches per epoch.
  • get_learning_rate(): Returns the learning rate per epoch.
  • get_training_time(): Returns the training time in seconds.
  • get_training_loss(smmothing=0.): Returns the training loss every 10 iterations. If smoothing is not 0, the loss is smoothed (weighted by smoothing).
  • get_accuracy(): Returns the accuracy.
  • get_roc(): Returns the false-positive rate, the true-positive rate, and the thresholds.
  • get_auc(): Returns the area under the curve.
  • get_precision_recall(): Returns the precision, the recall, and the thresholds.
  • get_ap(): Returns the average precision.
  • get_confusion_matrix(): Returns the confusion matrix as array.

Visualization¶

To create heat maps to visualize the model's decision making process, the classes CustomHiResCAM and CustomOcclusionMap in the file utils/Visualization.py can be used. The target layers to be passed as argument in the initialization of CustomHiResCAM are:

ResNet-18 and ResNet-50:

target_layers=['fundus.backbone.layer4', 'horizontal.backbone.layer4', 'vertical.backbone.layer4']

EfficientNetV2-L:

target_layers=['fundus.backbone.features.8', 'horizontal.backbone.features.8', 'vertical.backbone.features.8']
In [13]:
